<div class="prose">

<h2>The three questions</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>What can you see?</strong> Observation only — color, apparent size, surface features, clouds. No naming, no guessing.</li>
  <li><strong>What can you guess?</strong> Which of these could support life, and how would you decide? Every reason goes on the board.</li>
  <li><strong>What would you need to know?</strong> What data is missing? What would you measure or look up before answering with confidence?</li>
</ol>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">After the reveal</div>
  One of these four images is not like the others — and if you treated them all the same during questions 1 and 2, that's not a mistake, it's the lesson. Every source has an Origin. From here on, we check before we trust. That's <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a>, and it applies to images too.
</div>

</div>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll(".pg-card").forEach(function (card) {
    card.addEventListener("click", function () {
      card.classList.toggle("flipped");
      card.setAttribute("aria-pressed", card.classList.contains("flipped") ? "true" : "false");
    });
  });
  document.getElementById("pg-reveal-all").addEventListener("click", function () {
    document.querySelectorAll(".pg-card").forEach(function (c) {
      c.classList.add("flipped");
      c.setAttribute("aria-pressed", "true");
    });
  });
  document.getElementById("pg-reset").addEventListener("click", function () {
    document.querySelectorAll(".pg-card").forEach(function (c) {
      c.classList.remove("flipped");
      c.setAttribute("aria-pressed", "false");
    });
  });
</script>
